---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import TerminalWindow from "../components/TerminalWindow.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="How SqueezyAgent Works"
  description="How SqueezyAgent uses local static analysis to find code structure before spending model context."
  active="how"
>
  <section class="page-hero">
    <div class="page-hero-inner">
      <span class="eyebrow">architecture draft</span>
      <h1>Spend local CPU before paid model context.</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        SqueezyAgent puts a deterministic local analysis layer between the user
        request and the LLM. The agent asks your codebase what connects to what,
        then sends the model targeted evidence instead of billable search noise.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="flow">
      <div class="flow-step">
        <span>01</span>
        <strong>Parse</strong>
        <p>Tree-sitter extracts declarations, imports, outlines, tests, and call-like syntax.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="flow-step">
        <span>02</span>
        <strong>Index</strong>
        <p>A local index stores files, functions, modules, references, and tests.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="flow-step">
        <span>03</span>
        <strong>Look up</strong>
        <p>The agent asks for ownership, impact, callers, tests, and likely code slices.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="flow-step">
        <span>04</span>
        <strong>Pack</strong>
        <p>Results become small evidence packets with paths, hashes, and reasons.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="flow-step">
        <span>05</span>
        <strong>Act</strong>
        <p>The model reads exact slices, plans a patch, applies it, and verifies.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section band">
    <div class="grid-2">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="eyebrow">local analysis</span>
        <h2>Useful structure, with clear limits.</h2>
        <p>
          SqueezyAgent does not need a full compiler or language server before
          it can save tokens. It can use fast static analysis to find likely
          files, functions, callers, and tests, then fall back to bounded text
          search when local structure is not enough.
        </p>
      </div>
      <TerminalWindow title="symbol_context(AuthLayer)">
        <div class="terminal-body">
          <div class="terminal-line">
            <span class="green">decl</span>
            <span>crates/server/src/auth/layer.rs:18..44</span>
          </div>
          <div class="terminal-line">
            <span class="cyan">callers</span>
            <span>router.rs:62, session.rs:101, tests/auth_flow.rs:29</span>
          </div>
          <div class="terminal-line">
            <span class="amber">tests</span>
            <span>3 paired by module path and proximity</span>
          </div>
          <div class="terminal-line">
            <span class="muted">fallback</span>
            <span>uncertain edge; bounded text check suggested</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </TerminalWindow>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-header">
      <span class="eyebrow">what gets cheaper</span>
      <h2>Less paid search. More local evidence.</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="grid-3">
      <article class="card">
        <h3>Repeated reads</h3>
        <p>Receipts let unchanged file ranges come back as compact references instead of full text.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <h3>Broad search</h3>
        <p>Local structure narrows the target before grep or raw reads enter the loop.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <h3>Tool chatter</h3>
        <p>Intent-level tools answer "who owns this" and "what breaks" without shell archaeology.</p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
